      <!-- ============================================================
           SECTION XI — WHAT TO WATCH
           ============================================================ -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="wrap-narrow">
          <div data-reveal>
            <div class="section-tag">XI · Watch list</div>
            <h2 class="section-h">
              Between&nbsp;now<br />and&nbsp;the&nbsp;ruling.
            </h2>
            <p class="section-sub">
              Specific signals that, if they appear, will move our read.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="watch" data-reveal>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <b>Any signal from McCullough</b>
                <span
                  >Out-of-court speeches, law-review work, amicus invitations.
                  He is the keystone.</span
                >
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Whether Hurley issues further rulings</b>
                <span
                  >His role as the trial judge whose work SCOVA is reviewing
                  matters institutionally. Additional Hurley orders that SCOVA
                  does or doesn't disturb are signal.</span
                >
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Whether a ruling beats May 25</b>
                <span
                  >A pre-deadline ruling is more likely to be a clean Argument-2
                  strike (which gives clear marching orders — use the old map)
                  than a complicated multi-ground analysis.</span
                >
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Footnote-and-citation density of the eventual opinion</b>
                <span
                  >Heavy citation to <em>Vlaming</em> and Madisonian originalism =
                  Kelsey wrote it. Heavy citation to the 1912 line = McCullough or
                  Powell wrote it.</span
                >
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Russell's separate writing — or its absence</b>
                <span
                  >If Russell concurs separately rejecting Argument 1 but
                  joining on Argument 2, that's the strongest possible signal
                  that the wing held but on the narrowest defensible ground.</span
                >
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============================================================
           BOTTOM LINE
           ============================================================ -->
      <section class="bottomline">
        <div class="wrap-narrow">
          <div class="bottomline-tag">Bottom line</div>
          <h2 class="bottomline-h">It's&nbsp;going<br /><em>down.</em></h2>
          <p class="bottomline-deck">
            We think the amendment <b>gets thrown out</b>, but we are honest
            about the deck: institutional deference doctrine, no Virginia
            precedent for nullifying a statewide referendum on procedural
            grounds, and the political instinct of justices not to overturn a
            1.27-million-voter election all push uphill against the challenge.
            The reason we still land on strike is the asymmetry: <b
              >Republicans need 1 of 4 grounds. Democrats need 4 of 4.</b
            > That's the case.
          </p>
          <a href="/extras" class="bottomline-back">
